following is the negative likelihood ratio for this test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.42","1.58","3.75","2.38","0.08"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enegative likelihood ratio\u003C/strong\u003E is calculated using the formula (1-sensitivity)/specificity. In this case:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E(1-0.95)/0.60 = 0.05/0.60 = 0.08\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA negative likelihood ratio of 0.08 indicates this test is good at ruling out disease when negative, as values less than 0.1 provide strong evidence for ruling out a condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The negative likelihood ratio is calculated by dividing the false negative rate by the true negative rate (1-sensitivity)/(specificity).","A negative likelihood ratio less than 0.1 provides strong evidence to rule out a condition when the test is negative.","The negative likelihood ratio helps clinicians determine how well a negative test result rules out a condition."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56182"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17480"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56182"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:31:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T13:32:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10170"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70716"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"",